bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: Gerrit Lansing (1928-2018) was an American poet, editor, and critic. Born in 1928 in Albany, New York, and raised in northern Ohio, he studied at Harvard University and Columbia University. Lansing was a longtime friend and correspondent of poet Charles Olson, with whom he shared an interest in the occult. Lansing was a longtime resident of Gloucester, Massachusetts, where he lived with his partner Deryk Burton and operated occult bookstore Abraxas Books. Lansing edited and published the literary journal Set, and wrote collections of poetry including Heavenly Tree Grows Downward (North Atlantic Books, 1977), Heavenly Tree, Soluble Forest (Talisman House, 1995), and February Sheaf (Pressed Water, 2003).

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: Collections are processed to a variety of levels, depending on the work necessary to make them usable, their perceived research value, the availability of staff, competing priorities, and whether or not further accruals are expected. The library attempts to provide a basic level of preservation and access for all collections as they are acquired, and does more extensive processing of higher priority collections as time and resources permit.
This collection received a basic level of processing, including rehousing and minimal organization.

Information included in the Description of Papers note and Collection Contents section is drawn from information supplied with the collection and from an initial survey of the contents. Folder titles appearing in the contents list below are often based on those provided by the creator or previous custodian. Titles have not been verified against the contents of the folders in all cases. Otherwise, folder titles are supplied by staff during initial processing.
This finding aid may be updated periodically to account for new acquisitions to the collection and/or revisions in arrangement and description.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into nine series: I. Correspondence, 1945-2002. II. Writings, 1944-1998. III. Other papers, 1956-2002. IV. Photographs, circa 1970s, undated. V. Ken Irby papers, 1964-2008. VI. Stephen Jonas papers, 1958-2001. VII. Set records, 1960-1967. VIII. August 2019 acquisition, 1814-2018. IX. January 2020 acquisition, 1939-2003.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The collection spans the years 1814-2018 and consists of correspondence, writings, photographs, printed material, and other papers documenting the life and work of poet Gerrit Lansing. Correspondence includes letters from many poets, writers, and other associates, including Deryk Burton, Thomas Meyer, Charles Olson, and Jonathan Williams, as well as members of the Lansing family. Writings include both Lansing's work and writings and broadsides by other poets. The collection includes records relating to the publication of the literary journal Set, as well as writings, correspondence, and other papers relating to poets Kenneth Irby and Stephen Jonas.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series consists of correspondence to Gerrit Lansing from a wide variety of poets, writers, and others, as well as letters between Lansing and other members of the Lansing family. Literary and personal correspondence is organized alphabetically, and notable correspondents include Deryk Burton, Thomas Meyer, Charles Olson, and Jonathan Williams.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series includes correspondence, writings, materials related to the occult, annotated books, and personal papers of Gerrit Lansing, as well as papers of his partner Deryk Burton, poet Stephen Jonas, librarian John McGavern, and poet and translator David Rattray. There is also an extensive amount of writings by other authors. Materials date from 1814 to 2018, with the bulk dating from approximately 1950 to 2018.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Organized into eleven subseries: Correspondence, Writings, Occult Papers, Annotated Books, Personal Papers, Stephen Jonas Papers, Deryk Burton Papers, John McGavern Papers, David Rattray Papers, Writings of Others, and Audiovisual and Computer Media.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Consists of correspondence of Gerrit Lansing, his mother Alice Scott Lansing, and other family members. Most of Lansing's letters to his mother were written while he was a student at Harvard, during his travels in Europe after graduation, and when he was living in New York in the early 1950s. Lansing frequently describes his efforts to network with editors, publishers, and other contacts in New York, and activities of his social circle, which included Kenward Elmslie, John McGavern, John Ashbery, anthropologist Dorothy Willner, and composer Elie Yarden.

bioghist.p: Deryk Burton (1931-1997), a yacht captain, was born in England and emigrated to the United States. He was Gerrit Lansing's partner for almost 40 years and helped operate Abraxas Bookstore, which Lansing opened in 1982 in Gloucester.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: John McGavern (1926-2008) was director of the University of Hartford library system in Connecticut for 34 years. Born in Arlington, Massachusetts, McGavern graduated from Harvard University in 1949, and later received a master's degree in library science from Simmons College in 1959. He met and befriended Gerrit Lansing while both men were students at Harvard.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This subseries contains drafts of poems and other writings by John McGavern and correspondence with Gerrit Lansing. Lansing's letters to McGavern are sometimes enclosed with his poems. There is also one manuscript by Douglas Stafford, a Black high school English teacher and McGavern's partner for over 25 years.

bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: David Rattray (1946-1993) was a poet and translator. He was known for his translations of French writers Antonin Arnaud, René Crevel, and Roger Gilbert-Lecomte. Among his published works are the poetry collection Opening the Eyelid, and How I Became One of the Invisible, a collection of stories and essays.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: This series contains printed and manuscript sheet music, notes, and "In the Company of Love," a song cycle for soprano and piano, with poems by Gerrit Lansing and music by Bruce Wolosoff. Materials are dated from 1939 to 2003.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: Arranged alphabetically by folder title.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Includes notes by Lansing, a poetry broadside by Ange Mlinko, and writings and a letter in an unknown hand.
